  "eprint": {
    "title": "Stake-Bleeding Attacks on Proof-of-Stake Blockchains",
    "authors": [
      {
        "name": "Peter Gaži",
        "email": "gazi@iohk",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Aggelos Kiayias",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      },
      {
        "name": "Alexander Russell",
        "email": "",
        "affiliation": ""
      }
    ],
    "abstract": "We describe a general attack on proof-of-stake (PoS) blockchains\nwithout checkpointing.  Our attack leverages transaction fees, the\nability to treat transactions \"out of context,\" and the standard\nlongest chain rule to completely dominate a blockchain. The attack\ngrows in power with the number of honest transactions and the stake\nheld by the adversary, and can be launched by an adversary\ncontrolling any constant fraction of the stake.\n\n\nWith the present statistical profile of blockchain protocols, the\nattack can be launched given a few years of prior blockchain\noperation; hence it is within the realm of feasibility for PoS\nprotocols.  Most importantly, it demonstrates how closely\ntransaction fees and rewards are coupled with the security\nproperties of PoS protocols.  More broadly, our attack must be\nreflected and countered in any future PoS design that avoids\ncheckpointing, as well as any effort to remove checkpointing from\nexisting protocols.  We describe several mechanisms for protecting\nagainst the attack that include context-sensitivity of transactions\nand chain density statistics.",
    "keywords": [
      "blockchain",
      "proof of stake"
    ],
    "category": "Cryptographic protocols",
